The course presents an overview of the historical development of Norwegian, concentrating on the stages of Primitive Norse, Old Norse, Middle Norwegian and Modern Norwegian, as well as describing the most significant linguistic changes. The relation between spoken and written language in different periods is explained. There is special focus on the language situation and developments of the 19th and 20th centuries that resulted in the use of two official varieties of written Norwegian today. In describing present day Norwegian, an overview of the important reforms in the 20th and 21st century is given, and language political principles are clarified. Text examples illustrating different periods are analysed together.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim of the course is to give essential knowledge about the history of the Norwegian language, looking at different stages in the development of the language in historical change and characterising the language of each stage. By analysing texts from different periods, the students learn to know the main features of Norwegian, as well as its ties to its sister languages. In addition, the course lays out the relation between spoken and written language, their social and cultural conditions for development, thus creating a basis for understanding the linguistic situation in present day Norway.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After completing the course, the student: - names the different stages in the development of Norwegian; - connects Norwegian to its sister languages in a historical perspective; - analyses simpler language historical texts and uses them to characterise the stage of language development at hand; - understands the historical background of the language situation in present-day Norway; - explains the sociocultural ties between language and society.
